CAPE TOWN - Two men sustained minor injuries after the light aircraft they were onboard crash-landed at Cape Point on Thursday. According to provincial EMS spokesperson Deanna Bessick the aircraft made an emergency landing on Olifantsbos Road at around 1:30pm. The road between Olifantsbos and Link roads has been closed until further notice. "Western Cape Government Healthâ€™s EMS responded to an incident which involved a light aircraft that had to make an emergency landing on the Olifantsbos Road at Cape Point on Thursday afternoon. An ambulance and a rescue vehicle were dispatched. Two male patients sustained minor injuries and were transported to hospitals nearby by a private ambulance service. "Fortunately both patients were not seriously injured," said Bessick. SANParks spokesperson Lauren Clayton said the details surrounding the crash were unknown at this stage. "All emergency personnel were immediately informed and responded timeously. The light aircraft had two occupants who suffered minor injuries and have been transported to hospital for further examination. We'd like to wish the occupants a speedy recovery during this time. "The details surrounding the cause of the crash are unknown at this stage. "SANParks would like to thank the Table Mountain National Park staff, the SA Air Force, Cape Medical Response, SAPS Simonstown, Metro Search and Rescue, and the Simonstown Fire and Rescue Services for your prompt response," said Clayton. Cape Times